  "prompt": "What do teachers think of smart students?",
  "response": "Teachers generally have varied perspectives on smart students, but some common views include:\n\n1. Positive perspectives:\n- Smart students often make teaching more enjoyable\n- They can engage in deeper discussions\n- They help motivate other students\n- They're usually easier to teach\n- They can be good role models\n\n2. Potential challenges:\n- Some smart students might get bored easily\n- Some might be less motivated if not sufficiently challenged\n- They might need additional stimulation or advanced material\n- Some could become disruptive if not engaged\n\n3. Individual teacher attitudes:\n- Most teachers appreciate intelligent students\n- They often want to nurture and support their academic potential\n- Good teachers aim to challenge and inspire smart students\n- They try to prevent smart students from becoming complacent\n\n4. Balanced approach:\n- Teachers typically want to support ALL students, not just smart ones\n- They aim to help each student reach their individual potential\n- Smart students are seen as one part of a diverse classroom\n\n5. Cautions:\n- Teachers try to avoid showing favoritism\n- They want to ensure smart students don't feel isolated\n- They work to create inclusive learning environments\n\nThe specific perspective depends on individual teachers' experiences and teaching philosophies.",
